body:
Given the following code: <!-- Please provide a link to play.rust-lang.org -->

```rust
pub struct Foo {
    #[deprecated(since = "0.52.16", note = "use some other field instead")]
    pub is_project: bool
}

fn main() {
    let _ = Foo {
        is_project: false
    };
}
```

The current output is:

```
warning: use of deprecated field `Foo::is_project`: use some other field instead
 --> src/main.rs:8:9
  |
8 |         is_project: false
  |         ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
  |
  = note: `#[warn(deprecated)]` on by default
```

Ideally there should be no warning. Because it's nice to be allowed to use the simple way of constructing a struct, in which case there's no point in avoiding initializing deprecated structs to some default values, or am I the only one who thinks so? I just don't see how this warning can be useful in this use case.
